anyways i find how Slow decks work in Vanguard super interesting (when Bushiroad's designers allow decks to be slow, at least) because its mostly unique to Vanguard and its all due to how the Guarding System directly ties "Card Advantage" to "Survival" in a way other games don't

Actually I think the funniest part about this style of deck in Vanguard is when the GB8's got printed, the one that ended up being built around was... Spike Brothers. The De Facto Aggro deck, and it was so strong that Spikes are /still/ a GB8 Turbo deck

this type kind of stopped existing though because mechanics like Limit Break and Generation Break meant Most decks had some kind of big blow out threshold they were trying to get to, and identity was lost. Tho Demiurge is a good example of this style from later Vanguard

tho that classical definition of control /does/ exist, I completely forgot the 3rd style of control that Vanguard has; Build Up. Decks that /have/ a big blow-out play, and they need some sort of threshold to activate it. This would be Dark Irregulars and Genesis typically

these are effectively two sides of the same deck (stall until the opponent peters out) but I find it interesting because its not the classical definition of control of "last until your high cost extremely high value blow outs are usable"
Then there's the Value types which just continue generating card advantage for themselves until the opponent peters out (Oracle Think Tank, Angel Feather, Granblue)

also im not sure how well this applies to other TCGs, but in Vanguard I classify Slow decks in two ways:

There's the Control types that take away the opponent's options until they run out and lose (Link Joker, Nubatama, Megacolony)

on the subject of deck speeds of vanguard clans, great nature is a super fascinating one cuz it pretty decisively started as a Fast clan, trading card advantage for closing out games faster, but after Chatnoir it takes a sharp turn into being a Slow Value deck
